	&lt;em&gt;Screengrab via &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="http://drakeweather.com/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;drakeweather.com&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Tue, 21 Jan 2014 17:34:35 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/lol/drake-weather-forecast-rapper-yolo/</guid><category>LOL</category></item><item><title>Amazon could start delivering your stuff before you even order it</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/business/amazon-predictive-anticipatory-yesterday-shipping-delivery/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/6a/0e/6a0e64230f9b7a1adc9ab44025e402aa.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	In 2012, YouTube comedy group The Bilderbergers released a popular animated sketch called &amp;ldquo;Amazon Yesterday Shipping,&amp;rdquo; an extended joke about Amazon.com delivering the things you want before you even order them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;iframe class="youtube-player" frameborder="0" height="365" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/HA_gwzx39LQ?rel=0" title="YouTube video player" type="text/html" width="630"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	And while &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/amazon/"&gt;Amazon&lt;/a&gt; still hasn&amp;rsquo;t perfected time travel, the company now owns &lt;a href="http://pdfpiw.uspto.gov/.piw?Docid=08615473&amp;amp;homeurl=http%3A%2F%2Fpatft.uspto.gov%2Fnetacgi%2Fnph-Parser%3FSect1%3DPTO2%2526Sect2%3DHITOFF%2526p%3D1%2526u%3D%25252Fnetahtml%25252FPTO%25252Fsearch-bool.html%2526r%3D1%2526f%3DG%2526l%3D50%2526co1%3DAND%2526d%3DPTXT%2526s1%3D%252522anticipatory%252Bpackage%252522%2526OS%3D%252522anticipatory%252Bpackage%252522%2526RS%3D%252522anticipatory%252Bpackage%252522&amp;amp;PageNum=&amp;amp;Rtype=&amp;amp;SectionNum=&amp;amp;idkey=NONE&amp;amp;Input=View+first+page"&gt;a patent&lt;/a&gt; for &amp;ldquo;anticipatory package shipping,&amp;rdquo; a system that predicts what you&amp;rsquo;ll order and sends it to an Amazon facility near you, rerouting it to your address as soon as you click to pay.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	The &lt;i&gt;Wall Street Journal&lt;/i&gt; &lt;a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/01/17/amazon-wants-to-ship-your-package-before-you-buy-it/"&gt;reports&lt;/a&gt; that Amazon sees shipping time as the main reason people still purchase brick-and-mortar stores. The predictive shipping system is a way of snagging customers before they leave the house to visit Amazon&amp;rsquo;s competition.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3"&gt;
	The system will rely on all the data you&amp;rsquo;re already giving Amazon every time you shop, including &amp;ldquo;previous orders, product searches, wish lists, shopping-cart contents, returns and even how long an Internet user&amp;rsquo;s cursor hovers over an item.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3"&gt;
	There&amp;rsquo;s no word on when the technology will go into effect (or whether it already has), and Amazon hasn&amp;rsquo;t released an estimate of how much it&amp;rsquo;s expected to cut down on delivery times.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3"&gt;
	Amazon has been focused on faster deliveries in recent months. In December, it generated a ton of buzz by proposing a system of &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/business/amazon-drone-deliveries-are-coming/"&gt;package-delivering flying drones&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3"&gt;
	&lt;i&gt;Photo via &lt;/i&gt;&lt;a href="http://i.imgur.com/QGPoPIq.jpg"&gt;&lt;i&gt;listrophy&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;i&gt;/Reddit&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Sat, 18 Jan 2014 19:23:30 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/business/amazon-predictive-anticipatory-yesterday-shipping-delivery/</guid><category>Amazon.com</category><category>Business</category></item><item><title>Siri doesn't find your 'Her' jokes amusing</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/lol/siri-her-jokes-iphone/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/cb/ae/cbae51be12deb87f0b5edea930e0e6d3.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Spike Jonze&amp;rsquo;s latest film, &amp;ldquo;Her,&amp;rdquo; the tale of a man&amp;rsquo;s relationship with an intelligent operating system, has drawn critical raves and become an Internet obsession&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	It&amp;rsquo;s also drawn comparisons to Apple&amp;rsquo;s snarky digital personal assistant, Siri, who lives inside every recent iPhone. And Siri &lt;a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/jordanzakarin/if-you-ask-siri-about-her-she-throws-some-serious-shade"&gt;isn&amp;rsquo;t exactly flattered&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	How do we know? We asked her.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Apple&amp;rsquo;s cheeky programmers have given Siri a couple of snappy responses to the question &amp;ldquo;Are you Her?&amp;rdquo; For example,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
	&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
		&amp;ldquo;No. In my opinion, she gives artificial intelligence a bad name.&amp;rdquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
	&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
		&amp;ldquo;No, I don&amp;rsquo;t spend much time with purely fictional characters.&amp;rdquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	and&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
	&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
		&amp;ldquo;No, her portrayal of an intelligent agent is beyond artificial.&amp;rdquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Sounds like Siri&amp;rsquo;s a little jealous. Or maybe she&amp;rsquo;s still in shock from &lt;a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_SRhnis6f8"&gt;finding out that Steve Jobs is dead&lt;/a&gt;. Maybe it&amp;rsquo;s just me, but it seems like she hasn&amp;rsquo;t really been the same since that one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
