</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Sun, 05 Jan 2014 15:59:15 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/sherlock-spoils-everything-animation-leigh-lahav/</guid><category>Fandom</category><category>YouTube</category><category>Entertainment</category></item><item><title>The NSA has nearly complete backdoor access to Apple's iPhone</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/politics/nsa-backdoor-iphone-access-camera-mic-appelbaum/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/89/7d/897d5eadb4f334bd25491d4a764838a0.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	The U.S. &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/nsa/"&gt;National Security Agency&lt;/a&gt; has the ability to snoop on nearly every communication sent from an Apple &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/iphone/"&gt;iPhone&lt;/a&gt;, according to leaked documents shared by security researcher Jacob Appelbaum and German news magazine &lt;i&gt;Der Spiegel.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3"&gt;
	&lt;span class="s1"&gt;An NSA program called DROPOUTJEEP allows the agency to intercept &lt;/span&gt;SMS messages, access contact lists, locate a phone using cell tower data, and even activate the device&amp;rsquo;s microphone and camera.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;img alt="" src="//cdn0.dailydot.com/uploaded/images/original/2013/12/30/S3222_DROPOUTJEEP.jpg" style="width: 640px; height: 828px;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	According to leaked documents, the NSA claims a 100 percent success rate when it comes to implanting iOS devices with spyware. The documents suggest that the NSA needs physical access to a device to install the spyware&amp;mdash;something the agency has achieved by &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/news/nsa-malware-laptops-tao-der-spiegel/"&gt;rerouting shipments&lt;/a&gt; of devices purchased online&amp;mdash;but a remote version of the exploit is also in the works.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;big&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Update&lt;/strong&gt;: Apple &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/politics/apple-iphone-nsa-denial-dropoutjeep/"&gt;denies&lt;/a&gt; it helped build the NSA&amp;#39;s iPhone backdoor.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Appelbaum says that presents one of two possibilities:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Either [the NSA] have a huge collection of exploits that work against Apple products, meaning they are hoarding information about critical systems that American companies produce, and sabotaging them, or Apple sabotaged it themselves,&amp;rdquo; Appelbaum said at the Chaos Communication Conference in Hamburg, Germany.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;iframe class="youtube-player" frameborder="0" height="365" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/b0w36GAyZIA?rel=0" title="YouTube video player" type="text/html" width="630"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Do you think Apple helped them with that?&amp;rdquo; Appelbaum asked. &amp;ldquo;I hope Apple will clarify that.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	&lt;em&gt;Photo via &lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/26556945@N00/10156683996/in/photolist-gtvEij-i4xZt5-i4yEpR-i4xWwJ-i4yAt4-i4ye3G-hpsiRt-h9qcnD-ezjZAn-fN1dBw"&gt;Piro*&lt;/a&gt;/Flickr&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Mon, 30 Dec 2013 18:04:32 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/politics/nsa-backdoor-iphone-access-camera-mic-appelbaum/</guid><category>Tech</category><category>Politics</category></item><item><title>Review panel says NSA should stop storing Americans' phone records</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/politics/nsa-review-results-phone-records/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/d6/06/d606b6cdcb04d590d5027a9eecdb9129.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	The review panel appointed by &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/president-obama/"&gt;President Obama&lt;/a&gt; to make recommendations about the &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/nsa/"&gt;National Security Agency&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rsquo;s controversial surveillance programs has called for an end to the NSA&amp;rsquo;s database of U.S. phone records, the &lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/nsa-shouldnt-keep-phone-database-review-board-recommends/2013/12/18/f44fe7c0-67fd-11e3-a0b9-249bbb34602c_story.html"&gt;&lt;i&gt;Washington Post&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; reports.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	In a 300-plus-page report, the five-member panel made 46 recommendations, including ending spying on allied foreign leaders and banning government agencies from tampering with commercial software to break encryption.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	The panel also called for more oversight in the government&amp;rsquo;s use of powerful &amp;ldquo;zero-day&amp;rdquo; hacking exploits. A leaked intelligence community budget revealed earlier this year that the NSA spent &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/politics/nsa-software-bugs-vulnerabilities-zero-day-hacking/"&gt;$25 million on software vulnerabilities&lt;/a&gt; in 2013.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	On the issue of telephone data collection, the review board suggested that phone companies, not the NSA, should be storing Americans&amp;rsquo; records. To access that data, the NSA would have to get approval from the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court, the controversial body that oversees the agency&amp;rsquo;s requests for information from private companies.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	Phone companies would not be required to hold onto the records any longer than they currently do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	These recommendations are advisory only. President Obama will decide in January which items the government will act on. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	&lt;i&gt;Photo via &lt;/i&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/octal/493055930/sizes/l/"&gt;&lt;i&gt;octal&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;i&gt;/Flickr&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Wed, 18 Dec 2013 23:07:38 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/politics/nsa-review-results-phone-records/</guid><category>Politics</category></item><item><title>Twitter users rally against new blocking policy with #RestoreTheBlock</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/news/twitter-old-block-restoretheblock-campaign/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/65/eb/65eb83958a0fd8488f84448d1406f46e.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Users incensed at &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/communities/twitter/"&gt;Twitter&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rsquo;s changes to &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/news/twitter-block-function-harassment/"&gt;the ability to block accounts&lt;/a&gt; have started a campaign for the company to restore the feature to its previous functionality. They&amp;#39;ve turned #RestoreTheBlock into a trending topic.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	Until today, blocking a user would prevent that account from following you, seeing your timeline, and favoriting or retweeting your Twitter posts. Now, you won&amp;rsquo;t see the users you block on Twitter, but they&amp;rsquo;ll still be able to see and interact with your timeline.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p3"&gt;
	&lt;span class="s1"&gt;Twitter argues that &lt;/span&gt;the company is now public, and users&amp;rsquo; feeds should reflect that. &amp;ldquo;We want to reinforce that content in a public sphere is viewable by the world,&amp;rdquo;&amp;nbsp;Twitter spokesperson Jim Prosser said.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	But the change has many users worried about their privacy&amp;mdash;the &amp;ldquo;new block&amp;rdquo; won&amp;rsquo;t stop harassers from retweeting their victims and getting others to join in on their attacks.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	The new block has been compared to dealing with a stalker by putting on a blindfold or &lt;a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/kashmirhill/2013/12/12/blocking-people-on-twitter-now-just-mutes-them/"&gt;sticking your fingers in your ears&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p4"&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Twitter made a big mistake changing how block works; There were always workarounds but now harassers have advantage,&amp;rdquo; wrote &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/anildash/statuses/411270320574963712"&gt;Anil Dash&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p4"&gt;
	The outcry against the new block has been swift, with nearly 5,000 tweets posted on the #RestoreTheBlock hashtag within an hour of the change becoming public.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p4"&gt;
	Several change.org petitions have also sprung up, demanding that Twitter restore its old blocking policy. The most popular gathered &lt;a href="http://www.change.org/petitions/twitter-don-t-make-life-easier-for-harassers-don-t-change-your-blocking-feature"&gt;more than 1,200 signatures&lt;/a&gt; in less than an hour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p4"&gt;
	Prominent Twitter users supporting #RestoreTheBlock include authors William Gibson and Warren Ellis, and actor William Shatner. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet" lang="en"&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		Dear &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/twitter"&gt;@Twitter&lt;/a&gt; , &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23RESTORETHEBLOCK&amp;amp;src=hash"&gt;#RESTORETHEBLOCK&lt;/a&gt; is happening because your new block policy facilitates a spectrum of abuse on your service. Please listen.&lt;/p&gt;
	&amp;mdash; Warren Ellis (@warrenellis) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/warrenellis/statuses/411306584590262272"&gt;December 13, 2013&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet" lang="en"&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&lt;a href="https://twitter.com/safety"&gt;@safety&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/twitter"&gt;@twitter&lt;/a&gt; this non-blocked blocking is for the birds. It doesn&amp;#39;t stop them from tweeting and having their friends RT. Pls reconsider.&lt;/p&gt;
	&amp;mdash; William Shatner (@WilliamShatner) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/WilliamShatner/statuses/411303342304796672"&gt;December 13, 2013&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Twitter has yet to respond to the growing backlash against the policy change.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p4"&gt;
	&lt;i&gt;Photo by &lt;/i&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/48889057888@N01/8427949301/in/photolist-dQKrGH-dQKrcH-gim7Yo-gikZSi-gikJnu-gikMpm-gikWZf-gimapA-gimpGv-gim3xD-gimpc2-gikGpG-gikSL4-gikYnK-gimrzP-gim7iL-7UZkGA-7UZkTj-dQR37S-dQR33h-dQR3fJ-7CeoMB-8QSC5V-aH9kPv-eatbc5-8WXRVg-7UZkxN-7UZkPL-7UW7i4-7UZkMq-7UW7yD-8s4SfX-cJyFmA-7ZG49U-8GPeQt-8GSp3Q-8GPeZH-8GPeUc-8fZ5DW-7LPL1s-apJ4bC-drfLrA-avzAFw-avzAJE-avzAQs-avwXD4-avzAZL-anNLAE-anD7us-anD7T7-9iagJa"&gt;&lt;i&gt;Kevin Krejci&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;i&gt;/Flickr&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Fri, 13 Dec 2013 02:40:19 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/news/twitter-old-block-restoretheblock-campaign/</guid><category>News</category><category>Twitter</category></item><item><title>Lindsay Lohan is suing over 'Grand Theft Auto V'</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/gaming/lindsay-lohan-grand-theft-auto-v/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/a0/a8/a0a807037fac25d1c656010c8db456b3.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Lindsay Lohan is &lt;a href="http://www.tmz.com/2013/12/01/lindsay-lohan-grand-theft-auto-v-gtav-video-game-image-lawsuit/"&gt;suing Rockstar Games&lt;/a&gt;, developer of the insanely popular &lt;i&gt;Grand Theft Auto&lt;/i&gt; series, for allegedly using her image in &lt;i&gt;Grand Theft Auto V&lt;/i&gt; without permission.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	TMZ points out several parts of the game where Lohan could claim she appears, starting with the cover. The bikini model on GTA&amp;rsquo;s box and advertisements has been compared to everyone from actress Yvonne Strahovski to YouTube star Justine Ezarik to the one and only Kate Upton.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Could Lindsay really be the inspiration for the famous bikini babe?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Probably not. It&amp;rsquo;s already been confirmed that the image is based on model &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/gaming/gtav-grand-theft-auto-girl-bikini-model/"&gt;Shelby Welinder&lt;/a&gt;. Welinder even produced a copy of her invoice from Rockstar to prove it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	But a couple of characters in the game itself are significantly more Lohan-esque. One is Lacey Jonas, a vain celebrity who needs help escaping the paparazzi. The other lives in a building that TMZ claims resembles Hollywood&amp;rsquo;s famous Ch&amp;acirc;teau Marmont, where Lohan often stays. The player&amp;rsquo;s mission? To tape her having sex.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	TMZ has posted gameplay footage from the Lacey Jonas mission. Is she Lindsay? Decide for yourself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;iframe height="345” width=" id="kaltura_player_1385928062" src="http://cdnapi.kaltura.com/index.php/kwidget/wid/0_k6lajl8r/uiconf_id/6740162/st_cache/86635?&amp;amp;" style="border: 0px solid #ffffff;"&gt;Unfortunately your browser does not support IFrames.&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	However this turns out, Lohan is certainly going after some deep pockets. &lt;i&gt;GTA V&lt;/i&gt; holds the &lt;a href="http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/10/confirmed-grand-theft-auto-breaks-six-sales-world-records-51900/"&gt;Guinness World Record&lt;/a&gt; for fastest entertainment property to gross $1 billion.&lt;/p&gt;
