	ESPN&amp;rsquo;s College Gameday was at Auburn University on Saturday for the &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/lol/twitter-romeo-and-juliet-alabama-auburn-iron-bowl/"&gt;Iron Bowl&lt;/a&gt;, the annual football face-off between the Auburn Tigers and the Alabama Crimson Tide.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	But forget the game&amp;mdash;the big winner was a college kid caught on camera holding a sign that said &amp;ldquo;Hi Mom, send Bitcoin.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Fans of &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/bitcoin/"&gt;Bitcoin&lt;/a&gt;, the world&amp;rsquo;s most popular digital currency, spotted the sign on ESPN and loved it. And, thanks to the sign&amp;rsquo;s scannable QR code, they were able to find the student&amp;rsquo;s &lt;a href="https://blockchain.info/address/1HiMoMgBaAikFHgAt3M4YJtetp4HrnsiXu"&gt;Bitcoin address&lt;/a&gt; and start sending him money.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	At last count, he&amp;rsquo;s received 22 bitcoins, worth roughly $24,000.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	The clever sign-holder has only been identified by his &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/communities/reddit/"&gt;Reddit&lt;/a&gt; username, BitcoinPitcher2. On Reddit, he wrote that he never expected such a huge response, and wasn&amp;rsquo;t sure his QR code would even scan on TV.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Bitcoin has been on a massive upswing over the past week, &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/business/bitcoin-litecoin-black-friday-boom/"&gt;crossing the $1,000 threshold&lt;/a&gt; for the first time in its history.&lt;/p&gt;
