</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Sun, 24 Nov 2013 19:54:32 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/business/beastie-boys-goldieblox-viral-video-copyright/</guid><category>YouTube</category><category>Business</category></item><item><title>The case of the $150 million Bitcoin transfer may be closed</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/business/150-million-bitcoin-transfer-mystery-solved/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/1e/56/1e56c672df07e6b7ed7fba4ddcaf20af.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	On Friday, the tech world was abuzz with the news that someone had &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/news/bitcoin-150-million-largest-transfer/"&gt;transferred $150 million&lt;/a&gt; worth of &lt;a href="http://dailydot.com/tags/bitcoin/"&gt;Bitcoin&lt;/a&gt;, the world&amp;rsquo;s most popular digital currency, from one account to another.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	That&amp;rsquo;s a staggering 1.6 percent of all the bitcoins currently in existence.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	It&amp;rsquo;s possible to spot individual transfers like this thanks to the blockchain, a register of every transaction in the Bitcoin ecosystem&amp;mdash;but the blockchain doesn&amp;rsquo;t&amp;nbsp; reveal who owns a given account. So, who just moved a massive fortune in virtual currency?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	University of California San Diego computer scientist &lt;a href="http://cseweb.ucsd.edu/~smeiklejohn/"&gt;Sarah Meiklejohn&lt;/a&gt; may have &lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/11/23/heres-who-probably-did-that-massive-150000000-bitcoin-transaction/"&gt;found the answer&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	Meiklejohn, author of a paper on techniques that can reveal a Bitcoin account&amp;rsquo;s owner, told the &lt;i&gt;Washington Post&lt;/i&gt;&amp;rsquo;s Timothy B. Lee that the massive transfer likely came from Bitstamp, the second-largest Bitcoin exchange in the world.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	Many of the addresses that initially transferred bitcoins into the huge account are known to belong to Bitstamp, and transactions flowing out of the address often went to Bitstamp accounts. Meiklejohn believes the gigantic transfer&amp;mdash;which was later &lt;a href="https://blockchain.info/tree/98324324"&gt;broken down into smaller bits&lt;/a&gt; and spread among other accounts&amp;mdash;was some kind of &amp;ldquo;internal shuffling&amp;rdquo; at Bitstamp.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;img alt="" src="//cdn0.dailydot.com/uploaded/images/original/2013/11/23/transaction.png" style="width: 640px; height: 246px;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2" style="text-align: right;"&gt;
	&lt;small&gt;&lt;em&gt;Screengrab via blockchain.info&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	The explanation makes sense, although it&amp;rsquo;s far less romantic than some of the theories spread around Friday: That the account belonged to incarcerated black market baron Dread Pirate Roberts, that it was owned by the Winklevoss twins (of Facebook infamy), or even that it was controlled by mysterious Bitcoin inventor Satoshi Nakamoto.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	Boring as it may be, it looks likely that the biggest Bitcoin transfer on record was just business as usual.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	&lt;i&gt;H/T &lt;/i&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/11/23/heres-who-probably-did-that-massive-150000000-bitcoin-transaction/"&gt;&lt;i&gt;Washington Post&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;i&gt; | Photo via &lt;/i&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/105644709@N08/10867417104/"&gt;&lt;i&gt;antanacoins&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;i&gt;/Flickr&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description><author>jay@dailydot.com (Jay Hathaway)</author><pubDate>Sun, 24 Nov 2013 17:00:47 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://www.dailydot.com/business/150-million-bitcoin-transfer-mystery-solved/</guid><category>Tech</category><category>Business</category></item><item><title>Rob Ford tries to end crack scandal, but his hacking scandal is just starting</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/news/rob-ford-hired-hacker-crack-tape/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/02/7b/027bf261acf716818b415710aecfac6b.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Rob Ford, the embattled mayor of Toronto, has been plagued since May by rumors of a video that showed him smoking crack cocaine. Those allegations of drug use got a lot more serious last week, when &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/politics/rob-ford-crack-video-toronto-police/"&gt;police recovered the video&lt;/a&gt;, which has reportedly been viewed by at least four journalists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	With the tape apparently unlikely to disappear again&amp;mdash;as it did this summer after Gawker Media &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/news/rob-ford-crack-video-crackstarter-gawker/"&gt;raised $200,000 to buy it&lt;/a&gt;, only to see the supposed owners vanish before the deal went through&amp;mdash;Ford finally broke under questioning from reporters today.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	&lt;span class="s1"&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes, I have smoked crack cocaine,&amp;rdquo; he admitted, &amp;ldquo;&lt;/span&gt;Probably in one of my drunken stupors, probably approximately about a year ago.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1" style="text-align: center;"&gt;
	&lt;iframe class="youtube-player" frameborder="0" height="365" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/VsjlNNsChZ4?rel=0" title="YouTube video player" type="text/html" width="630"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p5"&gt;
	In a press conference, &lt;a href="http://www.latimes.com/nation/shareitnow/la-sh-toronto-mayor-rob-ford-crack-cocaine-20131105,0,290619.story#axzz2joUKsicX"&gt;Ford apologized&lt;/a&gt; for his transgressions and announced he would not resign as mayor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p6"&gt;
	&amp;quot;I know what I did was wrong, and admitting it was the most difficult and embarrassing thing I&amp;#39;ve ever had to do.&amp;nbsp; Folks, I have nothing left to hide.&amp;nbsp; I would do anything, absolutely anything to change the past.&amp;nbsp; But the past is the past, and we must move forward,&amp;rdquo; he said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p7"&gt;
	Ford&amp;rsquo;s apology only addressed his confession that he had smoked crack, and didn&amp;rsquo;t include a mention of the &lt;a href="http://dailyxtra.com/toronto/news/toronto-mayor-rob-ford-silent-homophobic-and-racist-comments?market=210"&gt;racist and homophobic statements&lt;/a&gt; he&amp;rsquo;s accused of making on the same video.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p7"&gt;
	To further complicate matters, Vice reports that Ford&amp;rsquo;s communications director, Amin Massoudi, &lt;a href="http://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/rob-fords-office-hired-a-hacker-to-destroy-the-crack-tape"&gt;hired a hacker&lt;/a&gt; in May in an attempt to suppress the release of the tape.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p8"&gt;
	Vice published emails that allegedly detail Massoudi&amp;rsquo;s arrangement with the hacker.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p8"&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Hey, it&amp;rsquo;s Amin,&amp;rdquo; Massoudi wrote in one message.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p9"&gt;
	&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;/span&gt;Man&amp;hellip; half my point was to keep this discrete, makes it hard to do when you drop your first name in the email.. smh,&amp;rdquo; the hacker responded.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;
	Vice unfolds a tale of increasing offers of pay&amp;mdash;including an offer to outbid Gawker&amp;rsquo;s $200,000 if the tape was removed from the server Ford&amp;rsquo;s office believed held the final copy&amp;mdash;and threats to bring more hackers into the project if their original contact couldn&amp;rsquo;t deliver.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	The hacker says Massoudi broke off their correspondence after it became clear the video wasn&amp;rsquo;t going to be deleted, but made an offer to &amp;ldquo;keep doing stuff like this in the future.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p2"&gt;
	Ford&amp;rsquo;s office hasn&amp;rsquo;t commented on the hacking allegations.&lt;/p&gt;
